# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1904-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The **1883 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1883.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American Association (AA) and eighth season for the National League (NL).
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics won the AA pennant, while the Boston Beaneaters won the NL pennant.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason, although there was a canceled exhibition series between the two pennant winners.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters of the National League folded.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] In its place, the league enfranchised two teams: the New York Gothams and Philadelphia Quakers (today's San Francisco Giants and Philadelphia Phillies).
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was decided that the six-team American Association would expand to eight teams and saw the minor league New York Metropolitans join and the enfranchisement of the Columbus Buckeyes.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Boston Red Caps and St.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings renamed as the Boston Beaneaters and St.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association and the National League, along with the Northwestern League, sign the Tripartite Agreement (also known as the National Agreement).
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This agreement binds the leagues to respect each other's valid player contracts as well as increasing the size of the reserve list from 6 to 11 players.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The 1883 schedule consisted of 98 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This format was unique to the 1883 season.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the National League had played an 84-game schedule, with 12 games against each team being played, while a pre-expansion six-team American Association had played an 80-game schedule, with 16 games against each team being played.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see the National League play a 112-game schedule (increase of 14 to 16 games each), while the American Association would expanded again, this time to twelve teams, for a 110-game schedule (of 10 games against each of the other eleven teams).
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all sixteen teams.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] American Association would see its final day of the regular season on September 30 featuring four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29, featuring all eight teams.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (1 in AA, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Eclipse and New York Metropolitans had one tie game each.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Detroit Wolverines had three tie games each.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons and Philadelphia Quakers had one tie game each.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Polo Grounds, home of the New York Metropolitans and Gothams, featured two baseball fields, at the southeast and southwest of the grounds.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Gothams played entirely at the southeast grounds, while the Metropolitans moved alternated.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The played ten games at the southeast diamond to start the season, before moving to the southwest diamond on May 30.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The southwest diamond was of worse quality than the southeast diamond, so games at the southwest diamond did not last long.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They played only ten games (aside from a one-off at the southeast diamond on June 13) before returning to the southeast diamond in July.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They did play three more games at the southwest diamond on August 30, 31, and September 4 due to scheduling conflicts with the Gothams.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Following a fire and a flood of their home at Exposition Park, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys had to move into a newly built venue, a second iteration of Exposition Park, which was built immediately south.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] However, after only 17 games, they played their last game there on June 9 and returned to the first Exposition Park on June 12.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The **1883 New York Gothams season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **San Francisco Giants**.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team replaced the Troy Trojans when the National League awarded its franchise rights to John B.
[src:1904-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team went 46–50, finishing in sixth place.
[src:1904-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The **1884 New York Gothams season** was the second season of that baseball franchise, eventually known as the San Francisco Giants.
[src:1904-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The team finished in fourth place, 22 games behind the pennant-winning Providence Grays.
[src:1904-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The **1886 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fourth season.
[src:1904-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The team had a record of 75–44, finishing third in the National League, 12.5 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1904-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The **1887 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fifth season.
[src:1904-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team finished in fourth place in the National League with a record of 68–55, 10+1⁄2 games behind the Detroit Wolverines.
[src:1904-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team amassed 415 stolen bases, the most for any team in the history of the National League.
[src:1904-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] The **1888 New York Giants season** was the franchise's sixth season.
[src:1904-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Claiming six future Hall of Famers (Roger Connor, Mickey Welch, Buck Ewing, Tim Keefe, Jim O'Rourke, and John Montgomery Ward), the team won the National League pennant by nine games and defeated the St.
[src:1904-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Keefe led the league in several major statistical categories, including wins, winning percentage, strikeouts, and earned run average.
[src:1904-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] The Giants beat the American Association champion St.
[src:1904-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Louis Browns in the World Series, six games to four.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] The **1904 World Series** was the scheduled championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 1904 season.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] It would have been contested between the champions of the two major leagues—the National League (NL) and the American League (AL)—as had been done in October 1903, the first modern World Series.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] The league champions in 1904 were the Boston Americans (now the Boston Red Sox) of the AL and the New York Giants (now the San Francisco Giants) of the NL.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] Boston had clinched their second consecutive AL pennant, while New York won the 1904 NL pennant by a wide margin, 13 games ahead of the Chicago Cubs.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] With still no formal arrangement in place between the two leagues regarding the staging of the World Series, the Giants under owner John T.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] Brush refused to play against a team from what they considered an inferior league.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] The resulting criticism from fans and writers caused Brush to reverse course during the offseason and lead the effort to formalize the World Series between the two leagues.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] The World Series was not a compulsory event and was not governed by an authoritative body.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] Thus, when the Boston Americans defeated the National League champion Pittsburgh Pirates in the 1903 World Series, the contest was arranged directly by the two champion clubs, not by the leagues themselves.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] During this time, there was an intense business rivalry between the two leagues, especially in New York.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] During spring training in March 1904, New York Giants owner John T.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] Brush said "there will never be a series" between the New York-based teams—his Giants of the National League and the American League's New York Highlanders (now the New York Yankees)—in response to a preseason offer from Highlanders co-owner Frank J.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] In July 1904, as reported in *Sporting Life*, Brush stated that his NL club would not play the AL club "if each wins the pennant in its respective league", in contradiction of a preseason agreement for a championship series between the leagues.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] The Giants won the NL by a wide margin (13 games).
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] The club then stuck to their plan, refusing to play *any* AL club in the proposed "exhibition" series (as they considered it).
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] Giants manager John McGraw, who had personal animosity with AL president Ban Johnson, said that his team was already the world champions because they were the champions of the "only real major league".
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] By July, the Highlanders were just 1+1⁄2 games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] The Highlanders then temporarily took over first place on October 7 when they defeated Boston.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] But the Americans won three of their four remaining games to clinch the AL pennant, and finished 1+1⁄2 games ahead of the Highlanders (who lost three of their final four games) in the final standings of October 10.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] Stung by criticism from fans and writers, Brush drafted rules that both leagues adopted in mid-February 1905.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] The rules compelled the two winning clubs to participate and governed the annual determination of sites, dates, ticket prices and division of receipts.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] These new rules essentially made the World Series the premier annual Major League Baseball event.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] Boston slumped in 1905, while New York repeated its NL championship and won the 1905 World Series against the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] The two teams eventually met in the 1912 World Series with the Red Sox winning in eight games (Game 2 was a tie).
[src:1904-world-series/1904-world-series] The Series has been played every year since except 1994, when a 232-day-long players' strike ended the season in mid-August.
[src:1904-world-series/giants-season] The **1885 New York Giants season** was the franchise's third season.
[src:1904-world-series/giants-season] The team finished in second place, 2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
